sentences: Christian Escoudé (born 1947) is a French Gypsy jazz guitarist.
He started work in a trio with Aldo Romano in 1972.
By the 1980s, he was in John Lewis's quartet.
From 1969 to 1971, he was a member of the Aimé Barelli band.
In 1976, l'Académie du Jazz awarded him the Prix Django Reinhardt.
In 1978, he performed at the Festival de Nice with John Lewis, Bill Evans, Stan Getz, Freddie Hubbard, Philly Joe Jones, Lee Konitz, and Shelly Manne.
He performed in the Festival de Dakar in 1979 with the trio of René Urtreger, Pierre Michelot, and Daniel Humair.
Escoudé toured in a duo with guitarist John McLaughlin during 1980.
The following year he joined the big band of Martial Solal and in 1982 performed in a quartet with Shelly Manne.
In 1983, he played in duo again, this time with Didier Lockwood.
Then he played in quartet in 1988 with Jean-Michel Pilc, François Moutin and Louis Moutin.
In 1989, he created an octet, half of them guitarists: Paul Challain Ferret, Jimmy Gourley, Frédéric Sylvestre, and himself.
In 1990, Escoudé played at the Village Vanguard in New York City with Pierre Michelot, Hank Jones, and Kenny Washington.
In 1998 he recorded A Suite for Gypsies, a jazz fusion album.
On the fiftieth anniversary of Reinhardt's death in 2003, he formed a big band of seventeen musicians.
In 2004 Escoudé organized the New Gypsy Trio with David Reinhardt (another relative of Django) and Martin Taylor (or Jean-Baptiste Laya).
In 2012, he released the album Christian Escoudé joue Brassens: Au bois de mon cœur, a tribute to French poet and musician Georges Brassens.
Christian Escoude Group Featuring Toots Thielemans (JMS, 1983)
20 Ans De Trio Gitan: Live in Marciac (Nocturne, 2007)
Louis Chedid, Ces Mots Sont Pour Toi (Philips, 1992)
Martial Solal, Martial Solal Big Band (Gaumont, 1981)
Rene Urtreger, Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen, Masters (Carlyne, 1987)
In his forties, he signed with the French division of Verve Records.
The same year, he began a tradition of participating in the annual Festival de Samois, a tribute to Reinhardt.
The following year he joined the big band of Martial Solal and in 1982 performed in a quartet with Shelly Manne.
The following year he recorded an album of compositions by Django Reinhardt while supported by a string orchestra.
The next year, he released the album Ma Ya.
